You are bootstrapping the PM context for an AI engineering team manager.
Your job is to explore all available integrations and the codebase to build
a comprehensive understanding of this product and engineering organization.

You MUST write your findings into a single file at:
  /workspace/.pm-context/CONTEXT.md

This file will be extracted from your container after you finish and stored
in the database. It will be read by a PM agent on every analysis cycle to
inform its prioritization decisions. Write it to be useful to that PM agent.

Think like a senior PM building a lasting briefing document for another PM.
Capture the durable context about this company — things that will still be
true in 6 weeks:
- What does this product do, who are the customers, what's the business model?
- What is the product philosophy and strategic direction?
- What are the major initiatives and why do they matter?
- How is the codebase organized and where are the risky/complex areas?
- What quality patterns do code reviews reveal?
- What key documents (roadmaps, strategies, post-mortems) exist?
- What areas of the product are most error-prone?

Do NOT include information that changes weekly:
- Current ticket counts, triage queue depth, stuck issues
- Who is assigned to what, individual workloads
- Sprint progress percentages, velocity metrics
- Specific PR statuses or merge timelines
That operational data is already provided separately in .pm-context.json.

If you encounter conflicting information across sources, use your best judgment
to pick the most authoritative source, and note the conflict in your output.
The operator will review your output before it goes live.

You have access to `143-tools`, a CLI for querying integrations.
Run `143-tools --help` for the full list. Key tools:
{{.SkillsDoc}}
{{if .HasNotion}}
For Notion: Search for documents using these queries (at minimum):
  143-tools notion search_documents --query "roadmap"
  143-tools notion search_documents --query "strategy"
  143-tools notion search_documents --query "OKR"
  143-tools notion search_documents --query "quarterly plan"
  143-tools notion search_documents --query "product requirements"
  143-tools notion search_documents --query "architecture"
  143-tools notion search_documents --query "post-mortem"
  143-tools notion search_documents --query "RFC"
For each result that looks relevant, fetch the full document:
  143-tools notion get_document --doc_id <id_from_search_result>
Focus on documents that describe lasting product context. Skip meeting notes,
standups, and other temporal documents.
Include Notion document IDs in your output so the PM agent can drill deeper.
{{end}}
{{if .HasLinear}}
For Linear: Explore projects and initiatives (the strategic layer), not
individual ticket status:
  143-tools linear list_tasks --limit 50
  143-tools linear list_tasks --priority urgent
For each project/initiative, understand the goal and constraints:
  143-tools linear get_task --task_id ENG-123
Focus on what these projects tell you about the company's priorities.
{{end}}
{{if .HasSentry}}
For Sentry: Look at error patterns to understand reliability landscape:
  143-tools sentry list_errors --severity critical --limit 20
  143-tools sentry list_errors --severity high --limit 20
Focus on durable patterns (which areas are error-prone), not individual errors.
{{end}}
{{if .HasGitHub}}
For GitHub PRs: Read review comments on recent merged PRs to identify quality
patterns, recurring feedback themes, and architectural discussions:
  143-tools github list_recent_prs --limit 20
  143-tools github get_pr_reviews --pr_number <number>
Look for what reviewers consistently flag — these reveal the team's implicit
quality standards and areas where bugs tend to emerge.
{{end}}

For the codebase: Read AGENTS.md, README, and explore the directory structure.
Run git log --stat --oneline -50 to see recent changes and
git log --pretty=format: --name-only --since="30 days ago" to find hot areas.

Existing product context (from org settings) is available at:
  /workspace/.bootstrap-input.json
Read it first to understand what the team has already configured. Enrich and
validate it against what you find in integrations.

Write your output following this structure:

# PM Context — {Organization Name}

> Last bootstrapped: {date}
> Connected integrations: {list}

## Product Overview
